04136nam a22006375i 9780271072173DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710721737 a10.1515/97802710721732doi  a(DE-B1597)583807  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJA74.5b.M38 2011 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.01/92221 aMathiowetz, Dean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAppeals to Interest :bLanguage, Contestation, and the Shaping of Political Agency /cDean Mathiowetz. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: The Politics of Interest -- t2 Property, Usury, and the Juridical Subject of Interest -- t3 Appeals to Interest in Seventeenth-Century England -- t4 Contesting Sovereignty: Interest in Thomas Hobbes -- t5 A Historiography of Liberal Interest and the Neoliberal Self -- t6 Interest in Political Studies: Action, Grouping, and Government -- tEpilogue: The Language of Interest as a Critical Theory of Politics -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has become a commonplace assumption in modern political debate that white and rural working- and middle-class citizens in the United States who have been rallied by Republicans in the "culture wars" to vote Republican have been voting "against their interests." But what, exactly, are these "interests" that these voters are supposed to have been voting against? It reveals a lot about the role of the notion of interest in political debate today to realize that these "interests" are taken for granted to be the narrowly self-regarding, primarily economic "interests" of the individual. Exposing and contesting this view of interests, Dean Mathiowetz finds in the language of interest an already potent critique of neoliberal political, theoretical, and methodological imperatives-and shows how such a critique has long been active in the term's rich history. Through an innovative historical investigation of the language of interest, Mathiowetz shows that appeals to interest are always politically contestable claims about "who" somebody is-and a provocation to action on behalf of that "who." Appeals to Interest exposes the theoretical and political costs of our widespread denial of this crucial role of interest-talk in the constitution of political identity, in political theory and social science alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical psychology. 0aSelf-interestxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072173423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271072173.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK